---
import Layout from '../../components/layout/Layout.astro';
import { blogPosts } from '../../data/blog';

export async function getStaticPaths() {
  return blogPosts.map((post) => ({
    params: { slug: post.id },
    props: { post },
  }));
}

const { post } = Astro.props;

const [year, month, day] = post.date.split('-').map(Number);
const formattedDate = new Date(year, month - 1, day).toLocaleDateString('en-US', {
  year: 'numeric',
  month: 'long',
  day: 'numeric',
});

const isStreamPost = post.id === 'how-stream-works-in-csharp';
const isMountPost  = post.id === 'accessing-windows-directories-from-linux';
---

<Layout title={`${post.title} — Raphael Coelho`} description={post.excerpt}>
  <div class="article-page w-full flex justify-center px-6">
    <article class="article-wrap w-full">

      <!-- Back link -->
      <a
        href="/my-portfolio/#blog"
        class="back-link inline-flex items-center gap-2 font-mono text-sm mb-10 transition-colors duration-200"
        aria-label="Back to blog list"
      >
        <svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" aria-hidden="true">
          <line x1="19" y1="12" x2="5" y2="12" />
          <polyline points="12 19 5 12 12 5" />
        </svg>
        Back to blog
      </a>

      <!-- Tags -->
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-5 flex-wrap">
        {post.tags?.map((tag) => <span class="tag">{tag}</span>)}
      </div>

      <!-- Title -->
      <h1 class="article-title font-mono font-bold text-3xl md:text-4xl mb-6 leading-tight">
        {post.title} 🤔
      </h1>

      <!-- Author byline -->
      <div class="article-byline flex items-center gap-3 mb-10 pb-8">
        <img
          src="/my-portfolio/images/avatar.jpg"
          alt="Raphael Coelho"
          width="40"
          height="40"
          class="article-avatar rounded-full"
        />
        <div>
          <p class="article-author font-mono text-sm font-semibold">Raphael Coelho</p>
          <time datetime={post.date} class="article-date font-mono text-xs">
            {formattedDate}
          </time>
        </div>
      </div>

      {isStreamPost ? (
        <div class="article-body space-y-14">

          <!-- Introduction -->
          <section>
            <p class="article-p leading-relaxed mb-4">
              Streams are a fundamental concept in C# for handling large amounts of data, network communication, and file I/O operations that may take time to complete. In many cases, the duration of these operations is unpredictable, so it's crucial to have a mechanism that doesn't block the entire process while waiting for results.
            </p>
            <p class="article-p leading-relaxed mb-4">
              Stream is an abstraction and they carry a sequence of bytes. Those bytes represent some information; an important aspect is that you don't need to load everything in memory when reading data through streams.
            </p>
            <p class="article-p leading-relaxed">
              Streams have some operations to make it possible to read through some information that still needs to be loaded. Those operations are <code>Read</code>, <code>Write</code>, and <code>Seek</code>. So let's talk about it 🧠
            </p>
          </section>

          <!-- Benefits -->
          <section>
            <h2 class="font-mono font-bold text-xl mb-4">Benefits of Using Streams 👍</h2>
            <ul class="space-y-3">
              <li class="flex gap-3">
                <span class="bullet">▸</span>
                <span class="article-p"><span class="font-semibold article-strong">Immediate Data Access:</span> You can read or write data even when the operation hasn't been fully completed, allowing for more flexible data handling.</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex gap-3">
                <span class="bullet">▸</span>
                <span class="article-p"><span class="font-semibold article-strong">Resource Efficiency:</span> Streams help minimize memory usage by processing data in chunks rather than loading everything at once.</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex gap-3">
                <span class="bullet">▸</span>
                <span class="article-p"><span class="font-semibold article-strong">Scalability:</span> Streams are ideal for scenarios where large-scale data processing is required, such as reading log files or streaming multimedia content.</span>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </section>

          <!-- Drawbacks -->
          <section>
            <h2 class="font-mono font-bold text-xl mb-4">Potential Drawbacks of Streams 👎</h2>
            <ul class="space-y-3">
              <li class="flex gap-3">
                <span class="bullet">▸</span>
                <span class="article-p"><span class="font-semibold article-strong">Complexity:</span> Working with streams can be more complex than dealing with static data, requiring careful handling to avoid issues like data corruption.</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex gap-3">
                <span class="bullet">▸</span>
                <span class="article-p"><span class="font-semibold article-strong">Error Handling:</span> Streams may require additional error handling, as network interruptions or file corruption can occur during streaming.</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex gap-3">
                <span class="bullet">▸</span>
                <span class="article-p"><span class="font-semibold article-strong">No Re-reading without Seeking:</span> Once you process a stream, you can't often go back to an earlier point without using the <code>Seek</code> method, which might not be supported by all streams.</span>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </section>

          <!-- Visualizing Streams -->
          <section>
            <h2 class="font-mono font-bold text-xl mb-4">Visualizing Streams 🧐</h2>
            <p class="article-p leading-relaxed mb-4">
              A helpful analogy for understanding streams is to think of them as faucets that allow data to flow continuously. Just like a kitchen faucet, the flow can be slow or fast, depending on the situation. Some streams might complete quickly, while others might take much longer.
            </p>
            <p class="article-p leading-relaxed mb-4">
              In this analogy, a <strong class="article-strong">buffer</strong> acts like a bucket. It catches the data as it flows, allowing you to access and process it. If the faucet (stream) is interrupted, the buffer retains what has been collected so far.
            </p>
            <p class="article-p leading-relaxed mb-6">
              Another important aspect is knowing where to resume reading data when the buffer is full. The stream's <strong class="article-strong">cursor</strong> plays this role — in the analogy, you can think of the cursor as the faucet's valve. It controls the water flow, allowing you to stop and start the stream as needed. The process of moving the cursor is called <strong class="article-strong">seek</strong>.
            </p>

            <!-- Diagram -->
            <figure class="my-10 flex flex-col items-center gap-3">
              <img
                src="/my-portfolio/images/blog/stream-diagram.png"
                alt="Diagram illustrating how a stream, buffer and cursor work together"
                class="article-diagram rounded-xl w-full"
              />
              <figcaption class="article-caption font-mono text-xs text-center">
                Stream, buffer and cursor — the faucet analogy
              </figcaption>
            </figure>
          </section>

          <!-- Reading File Content -->
          <section>
            <h2 class="font-mono font-bold text-xl mb-4">Reading File Content with a Stream in C# 🔥</h2>
            <p class="article-p leading-relaxed mb-8">
              Here's an example of reading data from a file using a <code>FileStream</code> class in C#. The <code>FileStream</code> class inherits from the abstract <code>Stream</code> class, which provides methods for handling streams.
            </p>
            <div class="code-block rounded-xl overflow-x-auto mb-8">
              <div class="code-header flex items-center gap-2 px-4 py-2 font-mono text-xs">
                <span>// FileStream read example</span>
              </div>
              <pre class="code-pre p-5 font-mono text-sm leading-relaxed overflow-x-auto"><code>using (FileStream stream = new FileStream(filePath, FileMode.Open, FileAccess.Read))
{'{'}
  byte[] buffer = new byte[1024];
  int bytesRead;
  while((bytesRead = await stream.ReadAsync(buffer, 0, buffer.Length)) > 0)
  {'{'}
    string content = Encoding.UTF8.GetString(buffer, 0, bytesRead);
    Console.WriteLine(content);
  {'}'}
{'}'}</code></pre>
            </div>
            <p class="article-p leading-relaxed mb-3">
              In this example, we read data from a file asynchronously using a buffer — an array of bytes. The data flows into the buffer partially, based on its capacity, and the <code>while</code> loop continues to refill the buffer until the entire stream is read. The <code>Position</code> property keeps track of the last read position via the cursor.
            </p>
            <p class="article-p leading-relaxed">
              We use <code>Encoding.UTF8.GetString(buffer, 0, bytesRead)</code> to transform the byte information into a string, but we can handle any type of information since we have it as an array of bytes.
            </p>
          </section>

          <!-- Stream Position & Flushing -->
          <section>
            <h2 class="font-mono font-bold text-xl mb-4">Handling Stream Position and Flushing 👀</h2>
            <p class="article-p leading-relaxed mb-8">
              If you need to reset the stream's position, check if <code>CanSeek</code> is true and use <code>Seek</code> to rewind to the beginning:
            </p>
            <div class="code-block rounded-xl overflow-x-auto mb-8">
              <pre class="code-pre p-5 font-mono text-sm leading-relaxed overflow-x-auto"><code>if (stream.CanSeek)
{'{'}
  stream.Seek(0, SeekOrigin.Begin);
{'}'}</code></pre>
            </div>
            <p class="article-p leading-relaxed mb-8">
              When working with writable streams, use <code>Flush</code> to ensure all buffered data is written to the underlying storage. This is critical to avoid data loss:
            </p>
            <div class="code-block rounded-xl overflow-x-auto">
              <pre class="code-pre p-5 font-mono text-sm leading-relaxed overflow-x-auto"><code>using (FileStream stream = new FileStream(filePath, FileMode.OpenOrCreate, FileAccess.Write))
{'{'}
    byte[] dataBytes = Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data);
    stream.Write(dataBytes, 0, dataBytes.Length);
    stream.Flush(); // Ensure all data is written to disk or transmitted
{'}'}</code></pre>
            </div>
          </section>

          <!-- Stream Lifecycle -->
          <section>
            <h2 class="font-mono font-bold text-xl mb-4">Stream Lifecycle ⏱</h2>
            <p class="article-p leading-relaxed mb-5">
              The lifecycle of a stream involves several key stages: creation, usage (reading, writing, seeking), and disposal. Understanding and managing each stage properly is essential for efficient and error-free operation.
            </p>
            <ul class="space-y-4 mb-6">
              <li class="flex gap-3">
                <span class="bullet">▸</span>
                <span class="article-p"><span class="font-semibold article-strong">Creation:</span> Streams are instantiated when a data source (file, memory, or network connection) is opened. Configuration parameters during instantiation, like file path, access mode, and buffer size, set up the stream's behavior.</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex gap-3">
                <span class="bullet">▸</span>
                <span class="article-p"><span class="font-semibold article-strong">Usage:</span> During usage, data flows through the stream via read, write, and seek operations. Each operation affects the stream's position, tracked by the internal cursor.</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex gap-3">
                <span class="bullet">▸</span>
                <span class="article-p"><span class="font-semibold article-strong">Flushing:</span> For writable streams, use <code>Flush</code> to push all buffered data to the underlying data source before the stream is closed, preventing data loss.</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex gap-3">
                <span class="bullet">▸</span>
                <span class="article-p"><span class="font-semibold article-strong">Disposal:</span> Streams implement <code>IDisposable</code> and should be disposed using a <code>using</code> statement, releasing file handles, network connections, or memory buffers.</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex gap-3">
                <span class="bullet">▸</span>
                <span class="article-p"><span class="font-semibold article-strong">Error Handling:</span> Implement <code>try-catch</code> around stream operations to handle file access issues, network timeouts, or data corruption gracefully.</span>
              </li>
            </ul>

            <p class="article-annotation font-mono text-sm mb-8">// Best practices</p>

            <div class="code-block rounded-xl overflow-x-auto mb-8">
              <pre class="code-pre p-5 font-mono text-sm leading-relaxed overflow-x-auto"><code>using (var stream = new FileStream(filePath, FileMode.Open, FileAccess.Read))
{'{'}
    // Perform read operations
{'}'} // Stream is automatically disposed here</code></pre>
            </div>

            <div class="code-block rounded-xl overflow-x-auto">
              <pre class="code-pre p-5 font-mono text-sm leading-relaxed overflow-x-auto"><code>using (FileStream stream = new FileStream(filePath, FileMode.Open, FileAccess.Read))
{'{'}
    if (stream.CanRead)
    {'{'}
        byte[] buffer = new byte[1024];
        int bytesRead;
        while ((bytesRead = stream.Read(buffer, 0, buffer.Length)) > 0)
        {'{'}
            string content = System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetString(buffer, 0, bytesRead);
            Console.WriteLine(content);
        {'}'}
    {'}'}
    else
    {'{'}
        Console.WriteLine("The stream does not support reading.");
    {'}'}
{'}'}</code></pre>
            </div>
          </section>

          <!-- Types of Streams -->
          <section>
            <h2 class="font-mono font-bold text-xl mb-4">Different Types of Streams in C# 🧬</h2>
            <p class="article-p leading-relaxed mb-5">
              While the examples above use <code>FileStream</code>, C# offers various stream implementations:
            </p>
            <ul class="space-y-3">
              <li class="flex gap-3">
                <span class="bullet">▸</span>
                <span class="article-p"><code class="article-strong">MemoryStream</code> — Stores data in memory; useful for temporary storage and operations that don't require disk writing.</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex gap-3">
                <span class="bullet">▸</span>
                <span class="article-p"><code class="article-strong">NetworkStream</code> — Allows data transmission over a network, often used for TCP/IP connections.</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex gap-3">
                <span class="bullet">▸</span>
                <span class="article-p"><code class="article-strong">CryptoStream</code> — Applies cryptographic transformations for secure data handling (encryption/decryption).</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex gap-3">
                <span class="bullet">▸</span>
                <span class="article-p"><code class="article-strong">BufferedStream</code> — Adds buffering to another stream, enhancing performance for repeated read/write operations.</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex gap-3">
                <span class="bullet">▸</span>
                <span class="article-p"><code class="article-strong">GZipStream</code> — Compresses or decompresses data using the GZip algorithm, ideal for reducing storage space and transmission time.</span>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </section>

          <!-- Conclusion -->
          <section>
            <h2 class="font-mono font-bold text-xl mb-4">Conclusion 🏁</h2>
            <p class="article-p leading-relaxed">
              Streams are a fundamental and versatile tool in C# that enable efficient data processing for large-scale I/O operations, such as file handling, network communication, and real-time data processing. By grasping the intricacies of stream usage — including performance optimization, effective error handling, and proper lifecycle management — developers can maximize the benefits of streams to build responsive, resource-efficient, and scalable applications. Understanding how to leverage different types of streams and applying best practices ensures that your applications handle data safely and efficiently, unlocking the full potential of this powerful 💪 concept in C# programming.
            </p>
          </section>

        </div>
      ) : isMountPost ? (
        <div class="article-body space-y-14" style="margin-top: 3rem;">

          <!-- Introduction -->
          <section>
            <figure class="my-10 flex flex-col items-center gap-3">
              <img
                src="/my-portfolio/images/blog/linux-mounting-hero.jpg"
                alt="Abstract illustration representing Linux and Windows file sharing"
                class="article-diagram rounded-xl w-full"
              />
            </figure>
            <p class="article-p leading-relaxed mb-4">
              In a mixed operating system environment, such as one that includes both Linux and Windows machines, users and teams often need a seamless way to access and share files across platforms. However, the inherent differences in file systems and protocols between Linux and Windows can complicate this process. For example, Linux typically uses ext4 or similar file systems, while Windows relies on NTFS, making direct compatibility a challenge. To bridge this gap, network file-sharing protocols become essential.
            </p>
            <p class="article-p leading-relaxed">
              One effective solution for such cross-platform file sharing is to use the CIFS protocol, which facilitates the mounting of Windows directories onto Linux, creating a unified, accessible file structure for both systems. In this article, we'll focus on using CIFS to mount a Windows directory onto Linux, providing clear access to Windows files from the Linux side.
            </p>
          </section>

          <!-- Concepts -->
          <section>
            <p class="article-p leading-relaxed">
              Before demonstrating how to set this up, let's first dive into some foundational concepts to understand the essentials of mounting and the CIFS protocol:
            </p>

            <h2 class="font-mono font-bold text-xl mb-4" style="color: var(--color-text);">What is Mount on Linux? 🐧</h2>
            <p class="article-p leading-relaxed mb-4">
              In Linux, "mounting" refers to the process of making a file system accessible within the directory tree, creating a link between the operating system and the storage device. After a file system is mounted, it becomes available at a specific location known as the <strong style="color: var(--color-text);">mount point</strong>, which serves as a doorway to access its contents.
            </p>
            <p class="article-p leading-relaxed">
              A good analogy to understand mounting is to think of a house. Imagine the house as the Linux file system, with its main entrance as the <code>/</code> directory (root). Adding a new device or file system to Linux is similar to adding a new room to the house. To access this room, you need a doorway — analogous to the mount point. The mount point is an existing directory path in the Linux file system where you attach, or "mount," the additional storage.
            </p>

            <h2 class="font-mono font-bold text-xl mb-4" style="color: var(--color-text);">What is a File System? 🗄</h2>
            <figure class="my-10 flex flex-col items-center gap-3">
              <img
                src="/my-portfolio/images/blog/linux-mounting-cifs-diagram.png"
                alt="Diagram showing how CIFS connects a Linux client to a Windows file server"
                class="article-diagram rounded-xl w-full"
              />
              <figcaption class="article-caption font-mono text-xs text-center">
                CIFS client-server model — Linux accessing a Windows shared folder
              </figcaption>
            </figure>
            <p class="article-p leading-relaxed">
              A file system organizes and manages how data is stored and retrieved on storage devices. It allows operating systems to create, read, update, and delete files. Different operating systems use various file system formats, like NTFS for Windows and ext4 for Linux. To access files from one system on another, the file system needs compatibility or a protocol like CIFS to bridge the gap.
            </p>

            <h2 class="font-mono font-bold text-xl mb-4" style="color: var(--color-text);">What is CIFS? 🌐</h2>
            <p class="article-p leading-relaxed mb-4">
              CIFS, or <strong style="color: var(--color-text);">Common Internet File System</strong>, is a protocol used for file sharing over networks, functioning as a dialect of the SMB (Server Message Block) protocol. Originally developed by IBM and later expanded by Microsoft, CIFS allows multiple users to access and share files and printers on a network.
            </p>
            <p class="article-p leading-relaxed">
              CIFS works on a client-server model, where a client requests a file or resource from a server over the network. After an initial request, a session is established, typically requiring authentication to ensure secure access. Once authenticated, the client can perform actions on the shared resources — reading, writing, deleting, or executing files and directories — as permitted by the server.
            </p>
          </section>

          <!-- Creating the Mount -->
          <section>
            <h2 class="font-mono font-bold text-xl mb-4" style="color: var(--color-text);">Creating the Mount 🔧</h2>

            <h2 class="font-mono font-bold text-xl mb-4" style="color: var(--color-text);">Step 1: Install CIFS Utilities</h2>
            <p class="article-p leading-relaxed mb-4">
              To mount a CIFS share, you'll need the <code>cifs-utils</code> package, which provides the necessary tools. Install it by running:
            </p>
            <div class="code-block rounded-xl overflow-x-auto mb-8">
              <pre class="code-pre p-5 font-mono text-sm leading-relaxed overflow-x-auto"><code>sudo apt-get update
sudo apt-get install cifs-utils</code></pre>
            </div>

            <h2 class="font-mono font-bold text-xl mb-4" style="color: var(--color-text);">Step 2: Create a Mount Point</h2>
            <p class="article-p leading-relaxed mb-4">
              Choose a directory where you want the CIFS share to be accessible. Create this directory as the mount point:
            </p>
            <div class="code-block rounded-xl overflow-x-auto mb-4">
              <pre class="code-pre p-5 font-mono text-sm leading-relaxed overflow-x-auto"><code>sudo mkdir -p /mnt/path_to_be_shared</code></pre>
            </div>
            <p class="article-p leading-relaxed">
              <strong style="color: var(--color-text);">Note:</strong> Ensure this directory is empty, as mounting a file system over an existing directory will make the directory's original contents temporarily inaccessible.
            </p>

            <h2 class="font-mono font-bold text-xl mb-4" style="color: var(--color-text);">Step 3: Mount the CIFS Share</h2>
            <p class="article-p leading-relaxed mb-4">
              Use the following command to mount the Windows share:
            </p>
            <div class="code-block rounded-xl overflow-x-auto mb-8">
              <pre class="code-pre p-5 font-mono text-sm leading-relaxed overflow-x-auto"><code>sudo mount -t cifs //WINDOWS_SERVER_IP/SharedFolder /mnt/path_to_be_shared -o username=WINDOWS_USER,password=WINDOWS_PASSWORD</code></pre>
            </div>
            <ul class="space-y-3 mb-4">
              <li class="flex gap-3">
                <span style="color: var(--color-accent);">▸</span>
                <span class="article-p">The first argument (<code>//WINDOWS_SERVER_IP/SharedFolder</code>) is the path to the Windows shared folder.</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex gap-3">
                <span style="color: var(--color-accent);">▸</span>
                <span class="article-p">The second argument (<code>/mnt/path_to_be_shared</code>) is the mount point.</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex gap-3">
                <span style="color: var(--color-accent);">▸</span>
                <span class="article-p">The <code>-t</code> option specifies the type of file system — here <code>cifs</code>.</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex gap-3">
                <span style="color: var(--color-accent);">▸</span>
                <span class="article-p">The <code>-o</code> option allows a list of mounting options, in this case specifying the username and password for Windows server authentication.</span>
              </li>
            </ul>

            <h2 class="font-mono font-bold text-xl mb-4" style="color: var(--color-text);">Step 4: Verify the Mount</h2>
            <p class="article-p leading-relaxed mb-4">
              To confirm the CIFS share is mounted successfully, run:
            </p>
            <div class="code-block rounded-xl overflow-x-auto mb-4">
              <pre class="code-pre p-5 font-mono text-sm leading-relaxed overflow-x-auto"><code>df -h | grep windows_share</code></pre>
            </div>
            <p class="article-p leading-relaxed">
              This command lists mounted file systems, filtering the output for entries related to the Windows share.
            </p>

            <h2 class="font-mono font-bold text-xl mb-4" style="color: var(--color-text);">Step 5: Unmounting the Share</h2>
            <p class="article-p leading-relaxed mb-4">
              When you no longer need access to the mounted directory, unmount it with:
            </p>
            <div class="code-block rounded-xl overflow-x-auto">
              <pre class="code-pre p-5 font-mono text-sm leading-relaxed overflow-x-auto"><code>sudo umount /mnt/path_to_be_shared</code></pre>
            </div>
          </section>

          <!-- Credentials file -->
          <section>
            <h2 class="font-mono font-bold text-xl mb-4" style="color: var(--color-text);">Creating the Mount with a Credentials File 🔐</h2>
            <p class="article-p leading-relaxed mb-8">
              For security, storing credentials directly in the command isn't recommended. Instead, create a credentials file and set the appropriate permissions:
            </p>

            <p class="article-annotation font-mono text-sm mb-3" style="color: var(--color-accent);">// Step 1 — create the credentials file</p>
            <div class="code-block rounded-xl overflow-x-auto mb-8">
              <pre class="code-pre p-5 font-mono text-sm leading-relaxed overflow-x-auto"><code>sudo nano /etc/credentials</code></pre>
            </div>

            <p class="article-p leading-relaxed mb-3">Inside the file, add your Windows credentials:</p>
            <div class="code-block rounded-xl overflow-x-auto mb-8">
              <pre class="code-pre p-5 font-mono text-sm leading-relaxed overflow-x-auto"><code>username=WINDOWS_USER
password=WINDOWS_PASSWORD</code></pre>
            </div>

            <p class="article-annotation font-mono text-sm mb-3" style="color: var(--color-accent);">// Step 2 — lock down the file</p>
            <div class="code-block rounded-xl overflow-x-auto mb-8">
              <pre class="code-pre p-5 font-mono text-sm leading-relaxed overflow-x-auto"><code>sudo chmod 600 /etc/credentials</code></pre>
            </div>

            <p class="article-annotation font-mono text-sm mb-3" style="color: var(--color-accent);">// Step 3 — mount using the credentials file</p>
            <div class="code-block rounded-xl overflow-x-auto">
              <pre class="code-pre p-5 font-mono text-sm leading-relaxed overflow-x-auto"><code>sudo mount -t cifs //WINDOWS_SERVER_IP/SharedFolder /mnt/path_to_be_shared -o credentials=/etc/credentials</code></pre>
            </div>
          </section>

          <!-- fstab -->
          <section>
            <h2 class="font-mono font-bold text-xl mb-4" style="color: var(--color-text);">What is fstab? ⚙️</h2>
            <p class="article-p leading-relaxed mb-6">
              The fstab file (located at <code>/etc/fstab</code>) is a configuration file that specifies which file systems should be mounted at boot. By adding the CIFS mount to fstab, you can automate the mounting process to ensure the Windows share is available each time the system starts. Here's an example entry:
            </p>
            <div class="code-block rounded-xl overflow-x-auto mb-8">
              <pre class="code-pre p-5 font-mono text-sm leading-relaxed overflow-x-auto"><code>//WINDOWS_SERVER_IP/SharedFolder /mnt/path_to_be_shared cifs credentials=/etc/credentials 0 0</code></pre>
            </div>
            <p class="article-p leading-relaxed mb-4">Each field specifies the following:</p>
            <ul class="space-y-3">
              <li class="flex gap-3">
                <span style="color: var(--color-accent);">▸</span>
                <span class="article-p"><span class="font-semibold" style="color: var(--color-text);">File system:</span> <code>//WINDOWS_SERVER_IP/SharedFolder</code></span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex gap-3">
                <span style="color: var(--color-accent);">▸</span>
                <span class="article-p"><span class="font-semibold" style="color: var(--color-text);">Mount point:</span> <code>/mnt/path_to_be_shared</code></span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex gap-3">
                <span style="color: var(--color-accent);">▸</span>
                <span class="article-p"><span class="font-semibold" style="color: var(--color-text);">File system type:</span> <code>cifs</code></span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex gap-3">
                <span style="color: var(--color-accent);">▸</span>
                <span class="article-p"><span class="font-semibold" style="color: var(--color-text);">Options:</span> <code>credentials=/etc/credentials</code></span>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </section>

          <!-- Conclusion -->
          <section>
            <h2 class="font-mono font-bold text-xl mb-4" style="color: var(--color-text);">Conclusion 🏁</h2>
            <p class="article-p leading-relaxed">
              Mounting a Windows directory on Linux using CIFS is a straightforward yet powerful way to facilitate cross-platform file sharing. By understanding how mounting works in Linux and utilizing tools like CIFS, you can seamlessly integrate Windows shares into a Linux environment. This approach is invaluable for businesses and individuals who require regular, secure access to files across diverse operating systems.
            </p>
          </section>

